Sentence: Meanwhile, Dolly's younger sister, Kitty, is courted by two suitors: Konstantin Levin, an awkward landowner, and Alexei Vronsky, a dashing military man
Kitty turns down Levin in favor of Vronsky, but not long after, Vronsky meets Anna Karenina and falls in love with her (Karenina) instead of Kitty
Anna enchants Levin, but her (Anna) success in pleasing Levin only fuels her (Anna) resentment toward Vronsky
Anna picks a quarrel with Vronsky, accusing him (Levin) of putting his (Levin) mother before her (Anna) and unfairly postponing plans to go to the country
She (Anna) resolves to meet Vronsky at the train station after his (Levin) errand, and she (Anna) rides to the station in a stupor
